4.Stack: 
    follows LIFO (Last In First Out)
    Push → Add element
    Pop  → Remove last element
    Peek → View top element
    There are 3 main ways to use Stack:
       1. Legacy Stack Class - Stack<Integer> stack = new Stack<>();
       2. Deque (Recommended) - Deque<Integer> stack = new ArrayDeque<>();
       3. LinkedList as Stack -  Deque<Integer> stack = new LinkedList<>();
    
  Stack Class (Legacy): public class Stack<E> extends Vector<E>
                        It is synchronized (thread-safe)
                        Slower due to locking
          🔹 Methods:
                  push(E item)
                  pop()
                  peek()
                  isEmpty()
                  search(Object o)

                  Stack<Integer> s = new Stack<>();
                  s.push(10);
                  s.push(20);
                  s.push(30);
                  System.out.println(s.pop());  // 30
                  System.out.println(s.peek()); // 20

          Internal Working of Stack:  
                  Since Stack extends Vector, internally: Uses Dynamic Array
                            Object[] elementData;
                    🔹 Push Operation:
                            Before: [10, 20]
                            push(30)
                            After:  [10, 20, 30]
                            Adds element at top (end of array)
                    🔹 Pop Operation
                            Before: [10, 20, 30]
                            pop()
                            After:  [10, 20]
                            Removes last element
                    🔹 Resize Mechanism - Same as ArrayList: New Capacity = Old + (Old / 2)
                    🔹 Time Complexity
                            Operation	  Time
                            push()	    O(1)
                            pop()	      O(1)
                            peek()	    O(1)
      Why Stack is NOT Recommended ❗
      Problems:
          Synchronized → slow
          Legacy class
          Extends Vector (bad design)
    
  Modern Stack (Using Deque) :
    🔹 Best Practice:
          Deque<Integer> stack = new ArrayDeque<>();
    🔹 Methods Mapping:
          Stack	    Deque
          push()	  addFirst()
          pop()	    removeFirst()
          peek()	  peekFirst()
    🔹 Example
          Deque<Integer> stack = new ArrayDeque<>();
          stack.push(10);
          stack.push(20);    
          System.out.println(stack.pop()); // 20
    🔹 Internal Working (ArrayDeque) 
          Uses Resizable Circular Array
          
          [ _, _, 10, 20, _ ]
                  ↑ head
          No shifting
          Uses head/tail pointers

    🔹 Why Faster?
          No synchronization
          Better memory usage
          No legacy overhead

Types of Stack (Conceptual)
    🔹 1. Array-based Stack
