 1. Deque (Double-Ended Queue) :
      🔹 Definition:
            Allows insertion/removal at both ends.Can act as: Queue and Stack
            Deque<Integer> dq = new ArrayDeque<>();
      🔹 Implementations:
            ArrayDeque ✅ (best)
            LinkedList
      🔹 Methods:
            addFirst()
            addLast()
            pollFirst()
            pollLast()
            peekFirst()
            peekLast()
      🔹 Use Cases
            Sliding window problems
            LRU cache
            Stack + Queue combo
      WHY Deque Can Do Both - Because it supports both ends
            Queue uses:
                  Insert → end
                  Remove → front
            Stack uses:
                  Insert → front
                  Remove → front
            Same structure → different usage
       Visual Understanding:
            Queue (FIFO)
                  Front → [10, 20, 30] ← Rear
                  Remove here ↑
                  Add here →
            Stack (LIFO)
                  Top → [30, 20, 10]
                  Remove & Add same side ↑
                  Deque (Both)
                  Front ↔ [10, 20, 30] ↔ Rear
1.A ArrayDeque:
      Deque<Integer> dq = new ArrayDeque<>();
      It implements: Deque which extends Queue
      FIFO when used as queue and Also supports deque
      Queue<Integer> q = new ArrayDeque<>();
      Hierarchy:
            Collection
               ↓
            Queue
               ↓
            Deque
               ↓
            ArrayDeque
      Internal Working: Uses Resizable Circular Array   
                  [ _, _, 10, 20, _ ]
                          ↑ head
                  No shifting like ArrayList
                  Uses head/tail pointers
                  Very efficient
   Time Complexity:
            Operation	Time
            offer()	O(1)
            poll()	O(1)
            peek()	O(1)
   ArrayDeque can behave as:
            ✅ 1. Stack (LIFO)
            ✅ 2. Queue (FIFO)
            ✅ 3. Deque (Both ends)

       1. Using ArrayDeque as Stack:  Behavior: LIFO
            Deque<Integer> stack = new ArrayDeque<>();
            stack.push(10);
            stack.push(20);  
            System.out.println(stack.pop()); // 20

      2. Using ArrayDeque as Queue: Behavior: FIFO
            Deque<Integer> queue = new ArrayDeque<>();
            queue.offer(10);
            queue.offer(20);
            System.out.println(queue.poll()); // 10

      3. Using as Deque (Both Ends)
            Deque<Integer> dq = new ArrayDeque<>();
            dq.addFirst(10);
            dq.addLast(20);
            dq.pollFirst(); // 10
            dq.pollLast();  // 20

 Why ArrayDeque is Powerful:
            Feature	            Benefit
            No synchronization	Faster
            No index                shifting Efficient
            Supports both ends	Flexible
            Better than Stack	      Modern

Circular Array Concept : Used in: ArrayDeque and ArrayBlockingQueue
