 2. PriorityQueue :
      Elements ordered by priority
      Not pure FIFO

      Queue<Integer> pq = new PriorityQueue<>();
      pq.offer(30);
      pq.offer(10);
      pq.offer(20);  
      System.out.println(pq.poll()); // 10
   Internal Working : Uses Min Heap (Binary Heap)
                          10
                         /  \
                       30    20
                  Rule:
                        Parent ≤ Children
                        Smallest element always at root
                  Heap Property:
                        Parent index = (i-1)/2
                        Left child = 2*i + 1
                        Right child = 2*i + 2
   Internal Representation:
           Internally uses array-based binary heap
           Not sorted fully — only root guaranteed smallest
           Iteration order ≠ sorted order ❗'

       Stored as array:
            Index:   0   1   2   3   4
            Value:  [10, 20, 30, 40, 50]
            Tree view:
            
                    10
                   /  \
                 20    30
                /  \
               40  50
            🔹 Step-by-Step Insertion (offer)
            Insert 30: [30]
            Insert 10:  [30, 10]
            Heapify Up:  10 < 30 → swap [10, 30]
            Tree:
                     10
                    /
                  30
            Insert 20:[10, 30, 20] No swap needed
            Insert 5: [10, 30, 20, 5]
            Heapify Up: 5 < 30 → swap [10, 5, 20, 30]
                        5 < 10 → swap [5, 10, 20, 30]
            Tree:
                          5
                         / \
                       10   20
                      /
                    30
         Removal (poll) — Step-by-Step
            Before removal: [5, 10, 20, 30]
            Step 1: Remove root (5) -  Replace with last element:  [30, 10, 20]
            Step 2: Heapify Down - 30 > 10 → swap [10, 30, 20] so 30 > 20 → swap, [10, 20, 30]
        
        Time Complexity:
                  Operation	Time
                  offer()	O(log n)
                  poll()	O(log n)
                  peek()	O(1)
    Custom Comparator: Queue<Integer> pq = new PriorityQueue<>((a,b) -> b - a); -> Max Heap

3. BlockingQueue (Multithreading):
      Special queue for producer-consumer problems
      Key Features: Thread-safe ✅
      Blocking operations:
            put() → waits if full
            take() → waits if empty
      Hireachy: 
            Collection
               ↓
            Queue
               ↓
            BlockingQueue   (thread-safe)
               ├── PriorityBlockingQueue
               ├── DelayQueue
               ├── SynchronousQueue
               ├── ArrayBlockingQueue
               └── LinkedBlockingQueue
      🔹 Examples:
            ArrayBlockingQueue
            LinkedBlockingQueue
      🔹 Behavior:
            Thread-safe
            Used in producer-consumer
            BlockingQueue<Integer> bq = new ArrayBlockingQueue<>(10);
            bq.put(10);   // waits if full
            bq.take();    // waits if empty
  3.A ArrayBlockingQueue: BlockingQueue<Integer> q = new ArrayBlockingQueue<>(5);
      Fixed size
      Thread-safe
      Uses circular array
  3.B LinkedBlockingQueue : BlockingQueue<Integer> q = new LinkedBlockingQueue<>();
      Optional bound
      Uses linked list
  3.C PriorityBlockingQueue
      Type: BlockingQueue + PriorityQueue behavior
      Internal:Heap (same as PriorityQueue)
      Sorted order (NOT FIFO)
      BlockingQueue<Integer> q = new PriorityBlockingQueue<>();
  3.D DelayQueue
      Type: BlockingQueue (time-based)
      Stores:Elements with delay
      Internal:PriorityQueue (heap based on time)
      Only available after delay expires
 3.E SynchronousQueue
       Type: BlockingQueue (special case)
      ❌ No storage at all
      Producer → directly handoff → Consumer
      Example:Thread communication

4. Concurrent Queues
            Collection
               ↓
            Queue
               ↓
            (Concurrent / Non-blocking Queues)
      ✅ They are Queue implementations
      ✅ They are thread-safe
      ❌ But they are NOT BlockingQueue
      
  Concurrent Queue Types:
       1. ConcurrentLinkedQueue
            Queue<Integer> q = new ConcurrentLinkedQueue<>();
            🔹 Belongs To Queue -> ConcurrentLinkedQueue Implements:  Queue and Serializable
            🔹 Internal Working: Lock-free linked list
                  Based on CAS (Compare-And-Swap)
                        [10] → [20] → [30]
                        Head & tail pointers updated atomically
                        No locking → high performance
            🔹 Behavior:
                  FIFO
                  Non-blocking
                  Thread-safe
            🔹 Methods:
                  offer()
                  poll()
                  peek()
      🔹 Use Case-High-performance systems: Messaging systems, Event queues and Real-time processing
      
      2. ConcurrentLinkedDeque:
            Deque<Integer> dq = new ConcurrentLinkedDeque<>();
      🔹 Belongs To
            Queue
               ↓
            Deque
               ↓
            ConcurrentLinkedDeque
      🔹 Internal Working: Lock-free doubly linked list
             [10] <-> [20] <-> [30]
      🔹 Behavior
            Works as: Queue (FIFO) and Stack (LIFO)
            Thread-safe
            Non-blocking
     
